<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Lacking Natural Simplicity (Posts about books)</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/</link><description></description><atom:link href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/categories/cat_books.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><copyright>Contents © 2020 &lt;a href="mailto:tkurtbond@gmail.com"&gt;T. Kurt Bond&lt;/a&gt; </copyright><lastBuildDate>Thu, 12 Mar 2020 17:01:41 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Dale E. Rippke's Kane Timeline &amp; Reflections on Planned but Unfinished Novels</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/dale-e-rippkes-kane-timeline-reflections-on-planned-but-unfinished-novels/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Dale E. Rippke over at the &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/"&gt;The Darkstorm Files&lt;/a&gt; has a wonderful
timeline, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/lord-of-chaos.html"&gt;Lord of Chaos&lt;/a&gt;, of Kane's adventures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He also has two interesting articles on the planned but unfinished
Kane novels, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/reflections-of-midnight-sun-by-dale.html"&gt;Reflections of a Midnight Sun&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/phantasmal-tomes-by-dale-e.html"&gt;Phantasmal Tomes&lt;/a&gt;, and another interesting article on the Kane/Elric crossover, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/rethinking-gothic-touch.html"&gt;Rethinking The Gothic Touch&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>dale e. rippke</category><category>kane</category><category>kane timeline</category><category>karl edward wagner</category><category>planned kane novels</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/dale-e-rippkes-kane-timeline-reflections-on-planned-but-unfinished-novels/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 12 Mar 2020 15:25:53 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Steve Tompkins on Sergio Leone and Karl Edward Wagner</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/11/steve-tompkins-on-sergio-leone-and-karl-edward-wagner/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;Over at &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.leogrin.com/CimmerianBlog/"&gt;The Best of the CIMMERIAN&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://dmrbooks.com/test-blog/2019/3/23/steve-tompkins-ten-years-gone"&gt;Steve Tompkins&lt;/a&gt; had a series of
articles in 2008 about Sergio Leone and Karl Edward Wagner: &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://leogrin.com/CimmerianBlog/something-to-do-with-deathlessness-part-one-violence-reigns/"&gt;Part 1&lt;/a&gt;,
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://leogrin.com/CimmerianBlog/something-to-do-with-deathlessness-part-two-eyes-we-dare-not-meet-in-dreams/"&gt;Part 2&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://leogrin.com/CimmerianBlog/something-to-do-with-deathlessness-part-three-splintered-shards-of-times-reflection/"&gt;Part 3&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description><category>fiction</category><category>karl edward wagner</category><category>movies</category><category>sergio leone</category><category>sword &amp; sorcery</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/11/steve-tompkins-on-sergio-leone-and-karl-edward-wagner/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 11 Mar 2020 22:37:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Robert E. Howard's The Hyborian Age at Gutenberg.org</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/11/robert-e-howards-the-hyborian-age-at-gutenbergorg/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;Here's the &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.gutenberg.org"&gt;Project Gutenberg&lt;/a&gt; ebook edition of Robert E. Howard's
essay “The Hyborian Age”, in &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/42182"&gt;different versions&lt;/a&gt; and in &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.gutenberg.org/files/42182/42182-h/42182-h.htm"&gt;HTML&lt;/a&gt;.  (See
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/"&gt;Wikipedia&lt;/a&gt; on the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hyborian_Age"&gt;essay&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyborian_Age"&gt;age&lt;/a&gt;.)  All here for later reference.&lt;/p&gt;</description><category>fiction</category><category>hyborian age</category><category>robert e. howard</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/11/robert-e-howards-the-hyborian-age-at-gutenbergorg/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 11 Mar 2020 21:28:58 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Sorcerer &amp; Sword's bibliography of Sword &amp; Sorcery fiction</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/07/sorcerer-swords-bibliography-of-sword-sorcery-fiction/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;In reading &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/01/recent-reading-flame-and-crimson/"&gt;Flame &amp;amp; Crimson&lt;/a&gt; I was reminded that Ron Edwards of
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://adept-press.com/"&gt;Adept Press&lt;/a&gt; published a supplement &lt;cite&gt;Sorcerer &amp;amp; Sword&lt;/cite&gt; for his RPG
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://adept-press.com/games-fantasy-horror/sorcerer/"&gt;Sorcerer&lt;/a&gt; (both copyrighted 2001) that has a chapter discussing
Heroic Fantasy, as he calls &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sword_and_sorcery"&gt;Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery&lt;/a&gt; fiction.  It's an
interesting read that mentions some authors and books that &lt;cite&gt;Flame &amp;amp;
Crimson&lt;/cite&gt; doesn't.  I've listed the authors and works from that chapter
below, with check marks (✓) for the ones I've read.  Edwards listed
some things more specifically that I have listed more generally.  He
breaks it down into several eras:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The originals: 1920s through 1950s&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_E._Howard"&gt;Robert E. Howard&lt;/a&gt; — The original &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conan_the_Barbarian"&gt;Conan&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories (Edwards has a
specific list of stories, but I think that all the original
R.E.H stories are worth reading), the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kull_of_Atlantis"&gt;Kull&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories, the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kull_of_Atlantis"&gt;Bran Mak
Morn&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories, and the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_Kane"&gt;Solomon Kane&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories, and
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almuric"&gt;Almuric&lt;/a&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;cite&gt;C. L. Moore&lt;/cite&gt; — &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jirel_of_Joiry"&gt;Jirel of Joiry&lt;/a&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clark_Ashton_Smith"&gt;Clark Ashton Smith&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Hyperborea&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Zothique&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Xiccarph&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;The Last
Incantation&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fritz_Leiber"&gt;Fritz Leiber&lt;/a&gt; — The Fafhrd and the Grey Mouser stories ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gardner_Fox"&gt;Gardener Fox&lt;/a&gt; — The Kothar and Kyrik books (though he notes that these
are at least 33% spoof)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norvell_W._Page"&gt;Norvell W. Page&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Flame Winds&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Son of the Bear God&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;The fans: 60s to early 70s&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Moorcock"&gt;Michael Moorcock&lt;/a&gt; — The &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elric_of_Melnibon%C3%A9"&gt;Elric&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories and the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corum_Jhaelen_Irsei"&gt;Corum&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories
(Edwards specifies the earlier stories from the 60s; I think all
of the Elric and Corum stories are worth reading)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poul_Anderson"&gt;Poul Anderson&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;The Broken Sword&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Hrolf Kraki's Saga&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poul_Anderson"&gt;Andrew J. Offut&lt;/a&gt; — (editor) &lt;cite&gt;Swords against Darkness&lt;/cite&gt;, vols. 1–5&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerald_W._Page"&gt;Gerald W. Page&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?Gerald_W._Page"&gt;GWP1&lt;/a&gt;) &amp;amp; &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hank_Reinhardt"&gt;Hank Reinhardt&lt;/a&gt; — The &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heroic_Fantasy_(anthology)"&gt;Heroic Fantasy&lt;/a&gt;
collection&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner"&gt;Karl Edward Wagner&lt;/a&gt; — The &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner#Kane,_the_Mystic_Swordsman"&gt;Kane&lt;/a&gt; ✓ stories and novels&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Betrayal: somewhere in the late 70s and beyond&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(This is Edwards' name for the era; these authors are ones he
considered as still writing good Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Amanda_Salmonson"&gt;Jessica Amanda Salmonson&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Tomoe Gozen&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;The Golden
Naginata&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Thousandshrine Warrior&lt;/cite&gt; ✓ (&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessica_Amanda_Salmonson#Tomoe_Gozen_trilogy"&gt;TG&lt;/a&gt;); (editor) &lt;cite&gt;Heroic
Visions&lt;/cite&gt;, vols. 1–2; &lt;cite&gt;Amazons&lt;/cite&gt;, vols. 1–2&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_J._Offutt"&gt;Andrew J. Offutt&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_L._Tierney"&gt;Richard Tierney&lt;/a&gt; – &lt;cite&gt;The Demon in the
Mirror&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;The Eyes of Sarsis&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Web of the Spider&lt;/cite&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?7082"&gt;David Mason&lt;/a&gt; (&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/mason_david"&gt;DM&lt;/a&gt;) — &lt;cite&gt;The Sorcerer's Skull&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Drake"&gt;David Drake&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;The Dragon Lord&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;The Mantichore&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_C._Smith_(author)"&gt;David C. Smith&lt;/a&gt; — The Oron series, the Master of Evil trilogy, &lt;cite&gt;The
Sorcerer's Shadow&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?115303"&gt;Victoria Graham&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;The Witchstone&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tanith_Lee"&gt;Tanith Lee&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Kill the Dead&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Night's Master&lt;/cite&gt; ✓ (The first of the
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tales_from_the_Flat_Earth"&gt;Tales from the Flat Earth&lt;/a&gt; ✓), &lt;cite&gt;Cyrion&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Volkhaavar&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Companions
of the Road&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Shea_(author)"&gt;Michael Shea&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Nift the Lean&lt;/cite&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?3957"&gt;Tim Lukeman&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Rajan&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;Koren&lt;/cite&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?123711"&gt;Gordon D. Shirreffs&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Calgaich the Swordsman&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darrell_Schweitzer"&gt;Darrell Schweitzer&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;We Are All Legends&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_R._Saunders"&gt;Charles R. Saunders&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Imaro&lt;/cite&gt; ✓, &lt;cite&gt;The Quest for Cush&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;The Trail of
Bohu&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Sherrell"&gt;Carl Sherrell&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Raum&lt;/cite&gt; ✓ (TKB adds: there's a sequel,
&lt;cite&gt;Skraelings&lt;/cite&gt; ✓)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;Karl Edward Wagner — (editor) &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Echoes_of_Valor"&gt;Echoes of Valor&lt;/a&gt;, vols. 1–3&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.fantasticfiction.com/t/keith-taylor/"&gt;Keith Taylor&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Bard&lt;/cite&gt;, &lt;cite&gt;Bard II&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also mentioned (sometimes for tone and mood rather than specific
stories or books):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._John_Harrison"&gt;M. John Harrison&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;The Pastel City&lt;/cite&gt; ✓ and &lt;cite&gt;Viriconium Nights&lt;/cite&gt; ✓
(TKB adds: the whole Viriconium series was republished in one
volume, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0553383159/"&gt;Viriconium&lt;/a&gt; ✓, and although the last two books are somewhat
weird the first two are definitely Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_Barrett_Jr."&gt;Neal Barrett, Jr.&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Kelwin&lt;/cite&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?7952"&gt;David Jarrett&lt;/a&gt; — &lt;cite&gt;Witherwing&lt;/cite&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Vance"&gt;Jack Vance&lt;/a&gt; — Some of the grimmer tales from &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dying_Earth"&gt;The Dying Earth&lt;/a&gt; ✓&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._P._Lovecraft"&gt;H. P. Lovecraft&lt;/a&gt; — the looming presence of Outer Dark horror&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Ligotti"&gt;T. Ligotti&lt;/a&gt; — “Masquerade of a Dead Sword” (TKB adds: this story
is in &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Songs_of_a_Dead_Dreamer"&gt;Songs of a Dead Dreamer&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>fiction</category><category>heroic fantasy</category><category>rpg</category><category>sorcerer &amp; sword</category><category>sword &amp; sorcery</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/07/sorcerer-swords-bibliography-of-sword-sorcery-fiction/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 07 Mar 2020 05:10:06 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Recent Reading: Ramsey Campbell - Far Away &amp; Never</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/06/recent-reading-ramsey-campbell-far-away-never/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;After reading &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/01/recent-reading-flame-and-crimson/"&gt;Flame and Crimson&lt;/a&gt; I went and bought several of the
Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery books it discussed.  Here is the first one I finished:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.amazon.com/Never-Ramsey-Stephen-Fabian-Campbell/dp/0940884860/"&gt;Far Away &amp;amp; Never&lt;/a&gt;, by Ramsay Campbell, copyright 1996,
Necronomicon Press, ISBN-10: 0940884860.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enjoyable collection of stories, avoiding the flaws of many of
the later sword &amp;amp; sorcery authors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The word-based magic in “The Stages of the God” and “The Song at the
Hub of the Garden” had a flavor of its own, and “The Ways of Chaos”
made me want to read &lt;cite&gt;Ghor, Kin-Slayer: The Saga of Genseric's
Fifth-Born Son&lt;/cite&gt; (&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://necropress.com/howard-et-al-ghor-kin-slayer-1/"&gt;G1&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.amazon.com/Ghor-Kin-Slayer-Saga-Genserics-Fifth-Born/dp/0940884917/"&gt;G2&lt;/a&gt;).  &lt;a class="footnote-reference brackets" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/06/recent-reading-ramsey-campbell-far-away-never/#genseric" id="id1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;dl class="footnote brackets"&gt;
&lt;dt class="label" id="genseric"&gt;&lt;span class="brackets"&gt;&lt;a class="fn-backref" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/06/recent-reading-ramsey-campbell-far-away-never/#id1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;
&lt;dd&gt;&lt;p&gt;Robert E. Howard left an unfinished story and many
decades after his death 16 top fantasy authors completed it by
writing sections in turn, each starting where the previous author
had left off.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/dd&gt;
&lt;/dl&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>fantasy</category><category>ramsey campbell</category><category>sword &amp; sorcery</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/06/recent-reading-ramsey-campbell-far-away-never/</guid><pubDate>Sat, 07 Mar 2020 03:31:38 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Recent Reading: Flame and Crimson</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/01/recent-reading-flame-and-crimson/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://www.amazon.com/Flame-Crimson-History-Sword-Sorcery/dp/1683902440/"&gt;Flame and Crimson: A History of Sword-and-Sorcery&lt;/a&gt;, by Brian
Murphy, copyright 2019, ISBN 978-1-68390-244-7.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A very good survey of Sword and Sorcery fiction, well worth reading.
I'm going to have to read it again and pull out all the books and
authors it mentions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
